-- #553 / #561 — the GENUINE-VALUE-CYCLE residual of the eager-init sort, the ONE
-- divergence #553 Stage B deliberately does NOT close (acceptance repro #5).
--
-- ⚠️ THIS FIXTURE IS WRONG ON PURPOSE, AND ITS GOLDEN ASSERTS THE BUG.
-- `eager_global_self_cycle.eval.golden` records native's ACTUAL output (`1`). The
-- RIGHT answer is a clean runtime error: `x` refers to itself during
-- initialization, a non-productive cyclic value. eval — the reference engine that
-- implements the DECIDED lazy-nullary semantics — raises `E-CYCLIC-VALUE` (exit 1)
-- by black-holing the cell. BOTH backends instead EAGER-initialize `x`'s cell to 0,
-- compute `0 + 1`, and print `1` at exit 0.
--
-- WHY STAGE B DOES NOT FIX IT. Stage B (the SCC-condensed eager-reachability
-- closure, backend/emit_support.mdk) makes the topo sort follow calls, closing the
-- call-hidden hole. But a topo sort has NO correct order for a genuine cycle: `x`
-- depends on `x`. Only laziness has an answer — black-hole and raise — which is
-- exactly what #561 (make top-level nullary bindings lazy on both backends) does.
-- So this stays a bounded, spec-recorded deviation, ledgered as
-- `emitter:shared-eager-init` in test/engine_divergence.txt and DRAINS when #561
-- lands (both backends start raising E-CYCLIC-VALUE, native stops printing 1, this
-- golden stops matching, and the ledger row promotes). Do NOT "fix" the golden to an
-- error while #561 is open, and do NOT delete this fixture.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines (2026-07-17); all three DIFFER, so the engines
-- gate records this fixture `na:ne:na:na:ran:ran` (native != wasm):
--   eval   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1        (correct)
--   native -> 1, exit 0                                     (a WRONG ANSWER, no diagnostic)
--   wasm   -> instantiate trap "dereferencing a null pointer", exit 1, NO output (not 1)

x = x + 1

main = x
